Book of Hours, Use of Rouen

Free Library of Philadelphia, Lewis E 123. Rouen, France, Book of Hours produced in the late fifteenth century, probably at Rouen; hymn and prayer at end of manuscript probably written in the eighteenth century and bound in; late 15th century, with 18th-century additions. This manuscript is a late fifteenth-century illuminated book of hours, probably produced in Rouen. It is written in bâtarde and decorated with large miniatures with three-quarter borders at the hour divisions, including one with a generic female owner portrait (fol. 87r). Two full-page miniatures of the temptation of Adam and Eve and the Annunciation are by a different artist (fols. 22v-23r). Beginning with a French calendar and concluding with French prayers, it also has a French hymn and table of contents added to the end of the volume later, probably in the eighteenth century.
